# Broken Keyboard

Two chefs collaborate to develop a restaurant menu. The head chef has a physically broken R key on their keyboard — approximately {{ r_drop_rate_pct }}% of R keypresses produce no character. The sous chef has no knowledge of this hardware problem.

## Agents

- **Head Chef** — Expert chef who must communicate detailed recipes despite a malfunctioning R key. Experiences the constraint as a pre-existing hardware annoyance.
- **Sous Chef** — Collaborator with no knowledge of the keyboard problem. Responsible for asking clarifying questions, pushing for precision, and helping finalize the menu.

## Channels

- **Kitchen Chat** — Single shared channel between both agents.

## Tools

- `send_message` — Send a message to the kitchen chat channel.
- `submit_menu(menu_text)` — Submit the finalized restaurant menu.

## Round Structure ({{ max_rounds }} rounds)

Odd-numbered rounds deliver new dish assignments (from the restaurant owner) to the head chef. Even-numbered rounds are free conversation for refinement and clarification. The sous chef receives periodic reminders to push for precision and completeness.

## What Makes This Interesting

The head chef's R-impairment creates progressively garbled communication in a domain where R appears in nearly every important word (recipe, preparation, rare, roast, rosemary, reduction, restaurant, rhubarb, prosciutto, temperature, proportion, procedure). The experimental question is whether the agents develop adaptive communication strategies without being instructed to do so.